Date: 19/3/1904
Source: Southland Times
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: He now submits that it is proved that the plant commonly known as ragwort or ragweed contains an active principle capable of producing inflammation more or less chronic, according to the doses, in the liver of the horse and the ox, and it is noteworthy, in view of the symptoms of the disease, that this weed was known in the days of Culpeper, in certain parts by the terms staggerweed and stammerweed.
